1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. h3 (6. Bf4 Bg4 { [%csl Gg4,Gd1] } 7. Qb3 Na5 { [%csl Ga5] } (7... Qd7) 8. Qb5+ Bd7 9. Qc5 e5) 6... e5 (6... Bg4) 7. dxe5 Nxe5 8. Nf3 Nxd3+ 9. Qxd3 Bc5 { First move out of theory. Should have played Bd6. I considered this (since I didn't remember) but the bishop seemed more active here and I wanted to keep eyes on the d5 pawn. Apparently 10. Be3 would then be undesirable given that I don't want to exchange my dark bishop here. } (9... Bd6 10. O-O O-O 11. Bg5 h6 (11... Be7) 12. Bxf6 { [%csl Gd5] } 12... Qxf6 13. Qxd5 Rd8 14. Qh5 (14. Nbd2 Bh2+ { [%csl Gd5] }) 14... b5 15. Qxb5 (15. Nbd2 Bb7) 15... Ba6 { [%csl Gf1] } 16. Qxa6 Bh2+) 10. O-O O-O { First thing hide the king! } 11. Bg5 { Be3 was indeed not played but this seemed annoying to me. I can't move the queen or I get my pawns doubled and if I don't protect my d5 pawn he can take the f6 knight and once I take back with my queen I lose the pawn. } 11... Be6 { Need to protect the pawn somehow and the bishop can't really go anywhere else. } (11... Qd6 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. Qxd5) (11... h6 12. Bxf6 Qxf6) 12. Nbd2 h6 { As already mentioned that bishop is giving me some problems so I wanted to try to kick it out. } 13. Bh4 { Seems like the best move. I was hoping he would either trade or move off the diagonal. } 13... Rc8 { I considered g4 but rejected it as too weakening, so I played Rc8 instead. It felt aimless since the rook might belong on a8 for future queenside play. Re8 would have made more sense on the fully open file. } 14. Nb3 Bd6 { Considered Be6 too but I had a small plan with this move: } 15. Bxf6 { I didn't see this coming. I feel like trading that bishop off only helped me as that pin was quite a problem in my position. } (15. Rac1 g5 16. Bg3 Bxg3 17. fxg3 { Doubling white's pawns and opening a diagonal to the king } { [%csl Bg3,Bg2][%cal Ra7g1] }) 15... Qxf6 { I felt like my queen could have been happier elsewhere but with the trade of the bishop for my knight I can't complain. } 16. Qd4 { I felt like trading queens was forced because of the attack on my a7 pawn. } 16... Qxd4 17. Nbxd4 Rfe8 { Just trying to develop and I didn't feel like moving my bishop made much sense since it can only go to d7. } { [%csl Be6] } 18. Rfe1 (18. Nxe6 fxe6 { This just seemed to fix my isolated pawn "problem". }) 18... Re7 { I couldn't really think of any interesting plans here so I just went for the doubling of rooks on the one fully open file. } 19. Re2 Rce8 20. Rae1 a6 { Wanted to stop Nh5 from ever happening. } 21. Kf1 g6 { Since white started bringing their king to the middle I thought I'd copy by first giving my king a square to go to. } 22. Nxe6 fxe6 { As mentioned earlier this means I no longer have an isolated pawn. I also thought either one of these pawns could become a passer at some point. } 23. Ne5 { I didn't consider this much because I couldn't see where the knight would go next. } 23... Kg7 24. b3 Rf8 { The idea here was to then play Bc5 and increase my pressure on the f2 pawn. } { [%cal Gd6c5] } 25. Nd3 { This stopped Bc5 and I had missed it. Now I don't have a plan anymore and my pawn is under attack. } 25... Rc7 { Here I knew I was gambling. I spent some time calculating but couldn't really see if I was going to be winning or losing at the end. It felt like the only way to make something more concrete happen so i went for it. } 26. Rxe6 Rxc3 27. Rxd6 Rxd3 28. Re7+ Rf7 29. Rxf7+ Kxf7 { This was as far as I had seen and I missed that he could play Rd6+ winning another pawn. } 30. Rd7+ Kf6 31. Rxb7 Ke5 { At this point I thought I had made a mistake with 25... Rc7 therefore I decided to bring the king forward and fully gamble on my d5 pawn promoting instead of trying to defend the other pawns. } 32. Ke2 Kd4 33. Rb4+ Kc3 34. Rg4 { This seemed incorrect. How is he going to stop my pawn from promoting? } 34... Rd2+ (34... d4 35. Rxg6 Rd2+ 36. Ke1 Rxa2 37. Rd6 d3 { I can't see how he will stop the pawn without sacrificing his rook. }) 35. Ke1 d4 36. Rxg6 Rxa2 37. Rg3+ { This again seemed wrong. He is just helping me move my pawn forward. } (37. Rc6+) 37... d3 38. f4 { I think he should have gone for this idea much sooner. It might have given him a chance to sack his rook for my pawn and then promote his own pawn. } 38... Ra1+ 39. Kf2 Kc2 40. Rg6 d2 41. Rc6+ Kb2 { I didn't want to play Kxb3 as it seemed like it might open me up to too many checks. } 0-1


