1. Nf3 e6 { With the goal of playing d5 next. } 2. g3 d5 3. Bg2 Nf6 4. b3 Be7 5. Bb2 O-O 6. O-O b6 7. d3 Bb7 8. Nbd2 Nbd7 9. Re1 c5 10. c4 $146 { First novel move } 10... Qc7 $14 { The idea was to connect my rooks and allow cxd5 as that would only help me keep my control of the center. } (10... d4 11. e3 dxe3 12. Rxe3 Qc7 $10 { This would have been better. The semi-open d file would have allowed me to add pressure on the now backwards d3 pawn. } { [%csl Bd3][%cal Bd8d3] }) 11. e3 Rad8 { Because of the unprotected pawn on d3 I placed my rook on the d-file eyeing it in case things ever opened up. } 12. Rc1 { Placing his rook in front of my queen. } 12... Rfe8 { Another slight improvement in case white ever took on d5, I would have the semi-open file after exd5. } 13. Qe2 (13. cxd5 exd5 { [%cal Be8e3] }) 13... Qb8 { Wanted to get my queen off the file where his rook is. } 14. d4 { Taking more space in the center. I was still no worried as him taking either my d or c pawn would only help me. } 14... h6 { A waiting move since I had no idea what to do. } 15. Ba1 { An interesting way to defend the bishop as it was his only loose piece in the position. } (15. dxc5 bxc5 16. cxd5 exd5 $15 { This would have been great for me in my opinion so I felt like leaving the tension in the center was fine. }) 15... Rc8 { Still didn't have a plan so I just copied his rook placement in case things ever opened up. } 16. a4 a5 { Didn't want to give him a chance to create any threats on the queenside. } 17. Red1 Qc7 18. Ne5 { The first interesting move. } 18... Nxe5 { I felt like since he would have to recapture with his d pawn this wasn't too bad and would result in him doubling his pawns and giving me a target to play against. } 19. dxe5 Nd7 { As mentioned his pawn is now a target. } 20. f4 { Defending his pawn. This seemed like he was starting to maybe weaken his kingside a little. Also his e3 pawn is now a weakness. } 20... f6 { Wanted to attack the e5 pawn further and had he taken (exf6) I would have been able to mobilize my pieces. I did feel quite crammed at this point so I wanted to maybe trade off the bishops and get some space back. } 21. Nf3 { He quite logically decided to defend his pawn instead of taking on f6. } (21. exf6 Bxf6 22. Bxf6 Nxf6 { This seemed like a pleasant position to end up in. }) 21... fxe5 { Here I took because I thought taking back with the f pawn would have left him with two weak doubled pawns on the e file and taking with the knight allowed me to develop my bishop to f6. Taking with the bishop seemed the worst of all since it's one of his best pieces. } 22. Nxe5 (22. Bxe5 Nxe5 23. Nxe5 Bf6 { This seemed great for me. }) (22. fxe5 { This seemed very poor for him. }) 22... Bf6 { As mentioned, this allows me to develop my bishop onto a better diagonal. } 23. Qh5 { This took me by surprise but I didn't really see the idea. I felt like his queen didn't really attack much here. } 23... Nxe5 { Since I felt quite crammed I thought trading pieces would give me some more space. In hindsight his pawn landing on e5 was quite annoying. } 24. fxe5 (24. Bxe5 Bxe5 25. fxe5 { This is what I was mostly hoping for but he obviously didn't want to trade his bishop. }) 24... Bg5 { I liked my position here since the attack on the e4 pawn seemed very strong and most options to defend it seemed poor. } 25. Rd3 Rcd8 { I regretted this move as soon as I played it. I only thought for 2 minutes and I feel like I could have easily found d4 or dxc4. } (25... d4 { The e3 pawn is pinned but if white doesn't take on d4 I will win a pawn and have a passed pawn on e3. There is also the threat of taking with the bishop and forking the king and the rook. } 26. Qe2 (26. exd4 Bxc1) (26. Bxb7 Qxb7 27. Rf1 Bxe3+ { Also winning an exchange. }) 26... Bxe3+ 27. Kh1 Bxc1 $19) 26. Rf1 Rf8 { Here again I missed d pawn related tactics. } (26... dxc4 { Not super clear to me why this is very strong. }) 27. h4 Rxf1+ 28. Bxf1 Be7 29. Bh3 d4 { Here I finally played d4. I liked that it opened up the diagonal for my bishop and allowed a simple move like Qc6 threatening a very strong attack. } 30. Bxe6+ { I saw that this pawn was hanging but after moving my king I didn't see any problems. } 30... Kh8 31. exd4 cxd4 32. Qe2 { This I felt was a mistake. } 32... Qc6 { With the threat of Qh1! } 33. Bd5 Rxd5 { I was very proud when I played this move. } 34. cxd5 Qxd5 { And the Qh1 threat is renewed. } 35. Kf2 Qg2+ { Here I knew I had a very strong attack and it was just a matter of finding the right moves. } 36. Ke1 Qg1+ { Obviously I didn't find the right moves. } (36... Bb4+ { I had considered this. But I thought that after: } 37. Kd1 Qg1+ 38. Qe1 { White was fine. Obviously when I look at it now I can see a slight problem in my visualization :) } 38... Qxe1+) 37. Qf1 Bb4+ 38. Ke2 Qxf1+ { Here I was getting low on time so I decided to go for what I thought was a draw... } 39. Kxf1 Ba6 40. Ke2 Bc3 { No need to rush in taking the rook since it can't move. } 41. e6 Kg8 { Ensuring I can stop the pawn. } 42. Bxc3 dxc3 43. Ke3 Bxd3 { Now I have to take before the rook moves. } 44. Kxd3 c2 { Thought this would help get his king further away from all the action... } 45. Kxc2 Kf8 46. Kc3 Ke7 47. Kc4 Kxe6 { And this is where my evaluation of the position was incorrect. I thought equals pawn, both kings in the middle = draw. } 48. Kb5 { This move obviously proved me wrong. } 48... g5 { Here I started realizing my mistake and I tried to go create a passed pawn of my own hoping we would both take equally as much time. } 49. Kxb6 Kf5 50. Kxa5 Kg4 51. b4 Kxg3 52. hxg5 hxg5 53. b5 Kh2 (53... Kf2 54. b6 g4 55. b7 g3 56. b8=Q g2 { Still lost but at least I could have advanced my pawn. }) 54. b6 { By this point I had realized I was completely lost. } 54... g4 55. b7 g3 56. b8=Q { And I can't even move my pawn. } 56... Kg2 57. Qxg3+ { A great move to simplify the endgame as much as possible. We were both low on time but with the 5 second delay there was no hope for me here. } 1-0


