eval -3.3] } { Inaccuracy. f4 was best. } { Wanted to advance my king on the queenside and this seemed best as it allowed me to play Kb2 and Kb3 without having to move the pawn again later. } (27. f4 Kd7 28. Rb3 Kc7 29. Ra3 Ra8 30. h5 gxh5 31. Rxh5 Rf2 32. Rh7 Rxf4) 27... Kd7 { [%eval -3.34] } 28. Kb2 { [%eval -3.3] } 28... Kd6 { [%eval -3.16] } 29. R1h2 { [%eval -3.25] } { This I wasn't sure about. I have a vague memory of having heard that trading one rook (when you both have two) favors the winning side so not me in this case. That said, his rook on g2 created some problems for me so trading it off felt like a small win. } 29... Rxh2 { [%eval -3.44] } 30. Rxh2 { [%eval -3.33] } 30... c5 { [%eval -2.93] } 31. c3 { [%eval -3.17] } { Only move that made sense to me. Taking worsens my pawn structure and allows him to bring his king even closer. I also like the prospect of having an a and b pawn against his lone a pawn potentially creating a passer in the future. Slight foreshadowing. } 31... cxb4 { [%eval -2.94] } 32. cxb4 { [%eval -3.31] } { Exactly as I had hoped. Now I might create a passed pawn in the future. } 32... e5 { [%eval -3.19] } 33. Kc3 { [%eval -3.84] } { I realized that his two pawns coming down the center were a more imminent threat than my b pawn trading its way thru so I decided to bring my king closer. } 33... Rc8+ { [%eval -3.84] } { Completely forgetting that this allows him to bring his rook with a tempo. } 34. Kb3 { [%eval -3.85] } 34... Rc4 { [%eval -3.12] } 35. h5 { [%eval -2.81] } { Only move that seemed logical to me. I have to try and open up something somewhere to create some potential for a blunder for black. } (35. a4 { This with the intention of playing b4 made sense too but with his rook on c4 my king would never be able to come help that pawn. }) 35... Rf4?? { [%eval 3.67] } { Blunder. gxh5 was best. } { And here I almost played hxg6. Luckily I thought for a second and realized I can squeeze a pawn thru. } (35... gxh5 36. Rxh5 Rc8 37. a4 d4 38. b5 axb5 39. axb5 Rc3+ 40. Kb4 Rxf3 41. Rh8) 36. h6! { [%eval 4.13] } { My opponent was a child (surprise surprise) and he spent the whole game walking around the room and our table and blitzing out each move. After I played h6 he finally sat down. :) } 36... Rxf3+ { [%eval 3.78] } 37. Ka4 { [%eval 4.32] } { In hindsight this was a loss of time. I should have calculated better and seen that after he goes Rc3 and Rc8 my king would be better on b2 where it doesn't block the a pawn. } 37... gxh6 { [%eval 4.16] } 38. gxh6 { [%eval 4.15] } 38... Rc3 { [%eval 4.0] } 39. h7 { [%eval 3.71] } 39... Rc8 { [%eval 4.48] } 40. h8=Q { [%eval 4.38] } 40... Rxh8 { [%eval 4.15] } 41. Rxh8 { [%eval 4.07] } 41... e4 { [%eval 3.94] } { Still pretty scary. I was very uncertain about what to do here. I considered all kinds of rook moves but they all felt like relative wastes of time. } 42. Kb3 { [%eval 4.14] } { I decided to bring my king backwards to add an eventual defender for all those damn pawns he had and also to open up the idea of playing a4 and b5 and creating another threat in the position. } 42... Ke5?! { [%eval 5.3] } { Inaccuracy. d4 was best. } (42... d4 43. Rd8+ Ke5 44. a4 e3 45. b5 axb5 46. axb5 Kf4 47. Rxd4+ Kg3 48. Re4) 43. a4 { [%eval 5.27] } { This felt so good to play. Completely ignoring his pawns and just pushing mine to create the obvious but unstoppable threat of making a queen. } 43... d4 { [%eval 6.56] } 44. b5 { [%eval 6.43] } { If he kept pushing his pawns on the d, e, f, and g files I would have all the time in the world to make a queen on b8 and I still always had the option to bring my rook down to the 1st rank to defend a promotion. On the other hand if he went for my pawn on the b file I would go eat all of his pawns with my king and rook and then we would be left with no pawns but I would have a rook. } 1-0


