1. e4 { [%eval 0.18] } 1... c6 { [%eval 0.31] } 2. c3 { [%eval 0.28] } { First new move for me. } 2... d5 { [%eval 0.26] } 3. e5 { [%eval 0.25] } 3... c5 { [%eval 0.23] } 4. d4 { [%eval 0.25] } { Here it transposed into the c3 line of the advanced caro which I am very comfortable with. } 4... Nc6 { [%eval 0.15] } 5. Nf3 { [%eval 0.0] } 5... cxd4 { [%eval 0.0] } 6. cxd4 { [%eval 0.0] } 6... Bg4 { [%eval 0.0] } 7. Be2 { [%eval 0.0] } 7... e6 { [%eval 0.0] } 8. O-O { [%eval 0.11] } 8... Nge7 { [%eval 0.05] } 9. Nc3 { [%eval 0.0] } 9... Nf5 { [%eval 0.04] } 10. Be3 $146 { [%eval -0.27] } { First move out of my repertoire. } 10... Bxf3 { [%eval 0.18] } { This move is fine but as always I'm overthinking the opening. Instead of the simple developing move Be7 I start trying to win the d4 pawn. } 11. Bxf3 { [%eval 0.19] } 11... Qb6 { [%eval 0.38] } 12. Na4 { [%eval 0.23] } 12... Qb4 { [%eval 0.47] } { I had seen all of this leading up to this moment but that's why I'm disappointed I played Bxf3 and went for this whole try. My bishop is still not developed and I'm at least two moves away from castling but I'm sending my queen out to try and maybe win a pawn if my opponent makes a mistake. Be7 would have been much better in my opinion. } 13. a3 { [%eval 0.46] } { This I hadn't predicted. I believe it goes to show why this whole line was a mistake by me. Now my queen is kicked around and I will not win the d4 pawn but white will get to develop and maybe fix all his problems. I need to get more comfortable with letting the pressure build slowly instead of trying to cash out right away. } 13... Nxe3 { [%eval 0.72] } { This move I thought was interesting as white can't take my queen. } 14. fxe3 { [%eval 0.73] } { But obviously white doesn't take my queen and ignoring the slightly awkward pawn structure in the center has a very fine position. } (14. axb4 Nxd1 15. Rfxd1 Bxb4 { I win a pawn. }) 14... Qa5 { [%eval 0.82] } 15. Qb3 { [%eval 0.55] } { Another move I didn't see coming and again an example of white developing with initiative white I am still at least two moves away from castling. } 15... b5?? { [%eval 3.35] } { Blunder. Rb8 was best. } { I thought this was my best hope for saving the pawn and creating some problems for white. Maybe hopefully... } (15... Rb8 16. Qc2 Be7 17. Bg4 Qc7 18. b4 Qd7 19. Be2 O-O 20. Rf3 Rbc8) 16. Nc3 { [%eval 3.13] } 16... b4?! { [%eval 4.74] } { Inaccuracy. Rc8 was best. } (16... Rc8 17. Nxd5 Nd8 18. Nf4 Be7 19. Rfc1 Rxc1+ 20. Rxc1 O-O 21. Qc3 Qa4 22. Qc2) 17. axb4 { [%eval 4.54] } 17... Qxb4 { [%eval 4.41] } 18. Qxb4?? { [%eval 0.98] } { Blunder. Bxd5 was best. } (18. Bxd5 Qxb3 19. Bxb3 Nxe5 20. Nb5 Rb8 21. dxe5 Bc5 22. Nd6+ Kd8 23. Ba4 Rf8) 18... Bxb4 { [%eval 0.97] } { And with the queens off the board my uncastled king and lack of space in the center should be less of a problem. } 19. Rfc1 { [%eval 0.5] } 19... Kd7?? { [%eval 2.64] } { Blunder. Ne7 was best. } { I thought this move was best. Bringing my king into the action while still safely hidden away and connecting my rooks. } (19... Ne7 20. e4 dxe4 21. Bxe4 Rd8 22. Rxa7 O-O 23. Rd1 Rb8 24. Kf1 Nc8 25. Rc7) 20. Ne2?? { [%eval -2.63] } { Blunder. Nxd5 was best. } { This looked like a clean blunder of a pawn by white. } (20. Nxd5 exd5 21. Bg4+ Kc7 22. Ra6 Rhb8 23. Rcxc6+ Kb7 24. Bf3 Rd8 25. Kf2 Rab8) 20... Bd2 { [%eval -2.53] } 21. Rd1 { [%eval -2.83] } 21... Bxe3+ { [%eval -2.85] } 22. Kh1 { [%eval -2.79] } 22... Rhb8 { [%eval -2.99] } { Bringing a rook into the game seemed important. From b2 my rook attacks a pawn and leaving the a8 rook in place felt necessary as I didn't want the c6 knight to be the sole defender of the a7 pawn. } 23. Rd3 { [%eval -2.95] } 23... Bf2? { [%eval -1.24] } { Mistake. Bg5 was best. } { I played this move because I was hoping white would allow me to win the d4 pawn as well. I think Bd2 is fine in theory but I mishandled the situation. } (23... Bg5 24. b3 Rb4 25. Rf1 Rab8 26. Bxd5 exd5 27. Rxf7+ Be7 28. Rxg7 Rxb3 29. Rxb3) 24. g3 { [%eval -1.38] } { g2 I had seen but I thought it was pretty harmless as it let me take the pawn on b2. Once g3 was played however I realized that if I took the pawn on b2 my bishop would be stuck. } (24. Rf1 Bh4 { Here my plan would have been to bring the bishop back and eventually play f6. }) 24... Rxb2?! { [%eval -0.64] } { Inaccuracy. Rb4 was best. } { So instead I went with Rxb2. My bishop is lost but I saw that if white attacks it with the king he looses another pawn. } (24... Rb4 25. Rad1 a5 26. Kg2 Bxd4 27. Nxd4 Nxe5 28. Ra3 Nc4 29. Rc3 Rxb2+ 30. Kg1) 25. Rf1 { [%eval -0.76] } { While if white attacks with the rook I found this exchange sacrifice that left me up three pawns and a knight for a rook. } (25. Kg2 Bxd4 { As the knight can't take due to the pin. }) 25... Rxe2?? { [%eval 3.75] } { Blunder. Bxd4 was best. } (25... Bxd4 26. Nxd4 Nxe5 27. Re3 f6 28. Ra1 Rb4 29. Nc2 Rc4 30. Bd1 a5 31. Rea3) 26. Bxe2 { [%eval 3.67] } { Only move I considered. } (26. Rxf2 Rxf2 { White obviously can't take. }) 26... Bxd4?! { [%eval 4.81] } { Inaccuracy. f6 was best. } { And this was the position I saw before playing 24... Rxb2. I have three pawns and a knight for a rook. With the a7 pawn being a passer and a 2 pawn majority on the kingside I thought I was definitely not losing and probably winning. } (26... f6 27. Rxf2 fxe5 28. dxe5 Nxe5 29. Ra3 a5 30. Rf1 Kd6 31. Rfa1 Nc6 32. Bb5) 27. Rxf7+ { [%eval 4.84] } { Then my opponent played this move... } 27... Ke8 { [%eval 4.7] } { At least I realized white was threatening to skewer my king and win the rook. } 28. Rxg7 { [%eval 4.15] } 28... Rd8 { [%eval 4.95] } { The skewer was threatened again so I had to bring my rook closer so my king could defend. I was debating between Rd8 and Rc8. Still don't know which is better. Rd8 places my rook behind the passed pawn on d5 and Rc8 places my rook on the open file allowing for checks and more mobility for the rook. } 29. Rxh7?! { [%eval 3.52] } { Inaccuracy. Bh5+ was best. } (29. Bh5+ Kf8 30. Rf7+ Kg8 31. Rc7 Nxe5 32. Rxd4 a5 33. Kg2 Rd7 34. Rxd7 Nxd7) 29... Bxe5 { [%eval 3.54] } { Here I was pretty annoyed with myself so I wasn't really calculating much. I thought that removing another pawn and being left with 3 passed pawns gave me the best odds. } 30. Bh5+ { [%eval 3.6] } 30... Kf8 { [%eval 3.49] } 31. Rf3+ { [%eval 3.51] } 31... Kg8 { [%eval 3.47] } 32. Rff7?! { [%eval 2.55] } { Inaccuracy. Rb7 was best. } { After this series of checks and Rff7 I felt like white wasn't playing this very well. His rooks here threaten very little. } (32. Rb7 Rf8 33. Rxf8+ Kxf8 34. Bg4 Nd4 35. Rxa7 Bf6 36. Kg2 e5 37. Rd7 Nc2) 32... d4?! { [%eval 3.57] } { Inaccuracy. a5 was best. } { As I mentioned before I was a little tilted so I wasn't calculating much at all. I saw white had no significant checks and just decided to push my pawn. } (32... a5 33. Bd1 Rb8 34. Kg2 Bd4 35. Rb7 Ra8 36. Ba4 Nb4 37. Rh4 Be5 38. Bd7) 33. Bg4 { [%eval 3.53] } 33... d3?? { [%eval #5] } { Checkmate is now unavoidable. Re8 was best. } { Here I was convinced that white would play Bxe6. } (33... Re8 34. Rd7 Kf8 35. Rh6 Rd8 36. Bxe6 d3 37. Rhh7 Bf6 38. Rxd8+ Bxd8 39. Rd7) 34. Rd7?? { [%eval 3.12] } { Lost forced checkmate sequence. Bxe6 was best. } { This looked pretty annoying but I didn't really see anything fatal. If at any point white takes my rook on d8 I can take back the rook on h7. } (34. Bxe6 d2 (34... Ne7 35. Rxe7+ Kf8 36. Rhf7+ Kg8 37. Rf5+ Kh8 38. Rh5#) 35. Rd7+ Kf8 36. Rhf7+ Ke8 { Looking at this now maybe I would have been fine. But in the moment I thought the capture on e6 would have been very bad news for me. } 37. Rxd8+ Nxd8) 34... Nd4 { [%eval 3.03] } { So I defended the pawn on e6 and blocked the rooks view of the d3 pawn. } 35. Rxd8+ { [%eval 3.1] } 35... Kxh7 { [%eval 3.04] } { As mentioned... } 36. Rd7+?! { [%eval 2.15] } { Inaccuracy. Rc8 was best. } (36. Rc8 Nc2 37. Bxe6 Kg7 38. Bb3 Ne1 39. Bd1 Kg6 40. h4 Kf5 41. h5 Bxg3) 36... Kg6 { [%eval 2.08] } 37. Rxa7 { [%eval 2.01] } 37... Kg5 { [%eval 2.17] } 38. Bd1 { [%eval 2.09] } { Here I got hopeful again. The position felt most definitely losing but it wasn't clear to me how white would have to go about it. } 38... Kf5 { [%eval 2.27] } 39. Kg2 { [%eval 2.03] } 39... Ke4 { [%eval 2.12] } { I have the most forward pushed pawn and the most active king. I also noticed that black's rook on a7 was a weakness. If black ever placed the king on the a7-g1 diagonal I might be able to fork it. } 40. Kf2 { [%eval 2.07] } 40... Ne2 { [%eval 2.52] } { Here I found this move and I was pretty happy with it. In my mind white had to move the rook as losing the exchange advantage would mean losing all his advantage. } 41. Bxe2?? { [%eval -0.06] } { Blunder. Ra6 was best. } { And here white fell right into my trap. } (41. Ra2 { White also would have had to be careful of where the rook went as there are potential tactics. } 41... Nc3 42. Ra1 Nxd1+ 43. Rxd1 Kd4 { Probably still losing for me but not super easy. }) (41. Ra6 Nc3 42. Bf3+ Kd4 43. Rxe6 d2 44. h4 d1=R 45. Bxd1 Nxd1+ 46. Kf3 Kd5) 41... Bd4+ { [%eval -0.33] } 42. Ke1 { [%eval -0.38] } 42... Bxa7 { [%eval -0.81] } 43. Bg4?? { [%eval -3.49] } { Blunder. Bf1 was best. } { Now we have an opposite colored bishop endgame with two pawns per side. I had a feeling this would be a draw but I knew that if it was winning for someone it was me as my pawns are much more advanced. I feel like there was a way for me to win this or at least try better for a win. } (43. Bf1 Bc5 44. g4 e5 45. h4 Kd4 46. g5 Be7 47. Kd1 e4 48. g6 Bf8) 43... e5 { [%eval -3.11] } 44. h4 { [%eval -2.53] } 44... Be3 { [%eval -1.72] } 45. h5 { [%eval -1.17] } 45... d2+? { [%eval 0.0] } { Mistake. Kd4 was best. } { This was the move I later regretted. IDK if it changed anything but it felt like putting all my pawns on dark squares meant that white could easily blockade with his king a bishop leaving me with no hopes for a win. } (45... Kd4 46. Kd1 Bh6 47. Bc8 e4 48. Bb7 e3 49. Bf3 Bg7 50. Ke1 Bf8 51. Bg4) 46. Ke2 { [%eval 0.0] } 46... Kd4 { [%eval 0.0] } 47. Bf3 { [%eval 0.0] } 47... Bg5 { [%eval 0.0] } 48. Bg4 { [%eval 0.0] } 48... e4 { [%eval 0.0] } 49. Kd1 { [%eval 0.0] } 49... e3 { [%eval 0.0] } 50. Bf3 { [%eval 0.0] } { And that's kind of what happened. } 50... Kd3 { [%eval 0.0] } 51. Be2+ { [%eval 0.0] } 51... Ke4 { [%eval 0.0] } 52. Bg4 { [%eval 0.0] } { Here I saw no way forward and offered a draw which my opponent obviously accepted. } 1/2-1/2


